{"hash":"f31bba29a5298f54a77d49aa89479d622b5583b9","data":{"blogPost":{"id":"a588b4ee5e9e9670807e4f3c0c3e46b6","title":"“The Statues” by Jacek Kaczmarski","description":"“Posągi” (1989) translated from Polish to English by Anna Karpiuk and Piotr Migdał: “What bliss when a tyrant’s tall statues are shattered”","path":"/blog/2019/10/the-statues-by-jacek-kaczmarski/","content":"<p>“Posągi” (1989) translated from Polish by Anna Karpiuk and Piotr Migdał</p>\n<p>What bliss when a tyrant’s tall statues are shattered<br>\nBut in each shard of bronze in each shrapnel of stone<br>\nThere lingers a trace of the spark that once fluttered<br>\nIn the one that was thrown from the throne</p>\n<p>And all men who saw the almighty’s rise and fall<br>\nAnd all new statues cast out of metal and dust<br>\nWill carry a splinter of the same tyrant’s soul<br>\nFact of life never to be discussed</p>\n<p>What bliss when a tyrant’s tall statues are shattered<br>\nBut a void on the plinth is what world cannot bear<br>\nFor statues are all made of one ancient matter<br>\nThat somewhere deep inside we all share</p>\n<p><figure class=\"md-figure-block\"><img class=\"g-image g-image--lazy g-image--loading md-figure-image\" src=\"data:image/svg+xml,%3csvg fill='none' viewBox='0 0 750 515' xmlns='http://www.w3.org/2000/svg' xmlns:xlink='http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink'%3e%3cdefs%3e%3cfilter id='__svg-blur-e6b95e5198758c01868e62561744f073'%3e%3cfeGaussianBlur in='SourceGraphic' stdDeviation='40'/%3e%3c/filter%3e%3c/defs%3e%3cimage x='0' y='0' filter='url(%23__svg-blur-e6b95e5198758c01868e62561744f073)' width='750' height='515' xlink:href='data:image/jpeg%3bbase64%%2bG4XECXNJz01J8CdzUFPh82IzKYMzxYWNvuPe3t61pcyzEE7xx6mvQlgrLIb3/kKxuBpQBC6zz7Fgl2e5%2blk66Jf52UAt0FJsx8xVDn2WNl7KERnUeQFzW5DD9WNzuBHtQ9mOm2xmIDEcf0qvUwIjlC0cNt95dNVywfCZi7Zw%2bXYqL6m3ch22ItyVP4tzVwuGeWwVLEgCiD4n6ThyzDQ51h1dsZhmAKqQoYDkE%2btj%2bwSKttDrgM6yaDMVkgjZrrJEW5Rx3HP/AFjSKuElwi2qs4LbWRjmVDmg2Pt%2bKgiyCaU7zwLeQqVh9N2S7cgcHnz9KI8/1Rp3TuCln